Mathematical Foundations of Non-Equilibrium Vacuum Dynamics: Multi-Scale Casimir Interactions, Back-Reaction, and Constraints from Semiclassical Gravity

Author: Ouadi Maakoul
Date: March 2026

---

Abstract

This thesis develops a comprehensive mathematical framework for understanding non-equilibrium quantum vacuum interactions under multi-scale boundary conditions. While the static Casimir effect is well understood within quantum electrodynamics (QED), and the dynamical Casimir effect (DCE) has been explored for single-frequency driving, the regime of simultaneous, incommensurate mechanical, electromagnetic, and topological modulations remains unexplored in its full generality, particularly concerning systematic back-reaction and semiclassical gravity implications. We construct a general path integral and mode-decomposition formalism for the electromagnetic field in cavities with time-dependent boundaries evolving on multiple frequency scales. By systematically deriving the coupled mode equations, Bogoliubov transformations, and the back-reaction stress-energy tensor, we establish rigorous connections between multi-scale driving, photon pair production spectra, vacuum friction, and the generation of spacetime metric perturbations within semiclassical gravity. Key novel results include: (i) a general expression for the particle spectrum as a sum over integer lattices of driving frequencies (Theorem 4.1); (ii) the vacuum impedance tensor characterizing the response to multi-frequency boundary perturbations; (iii) predictions of enhanced resonance, squeezing at beat frequencies, and a rich vacuum friction spectrum (Proposition 5.1); (iv) a classification of non-equilibrium vacuum states based on driving symmetries and mode structure (Theorem 6.1); and (v) rigorous upper bounds on the stress-energy achievable via boundary engineering (Theorem 7.1), demonstrating the impossibility of macroscopic "warp drive" or "inertial mass reduction" within known physics. This thesis extends the dynamical Casimir framework to genuinely multi-scale regimes, predicting observable signatures testable in superconducting circuits and optomechanics, while rigorously bounding vacuum-engineered stress-energy far below levels needed for macroscopic spacetime manipulation.

