Chapter 5

Back-Reaction and Vacuum Friction

5.1 Stress-Energy Tensor in Non-Stationary Cavities

The stress-energy tensor operator for the scalar field is

T_{\mu\nu} = \partial_\mu\phi\partial_\nu\phi - \frac{1}{2} g_{\mu\nu} (\partial_\alpha\phi\partial^\alpha\phi). 

Its expectation value in the time-dependent vacuum state is computed via point-splitting regularization. Define the Feynman propagator

G(x,x') = i \langle T \phi(x)\phi(x') \rangle. 

Then

\langle T_{\mu\nu}(x) \rangle = \lim_{x'\to x} \mathcal{D}_{\mu\nu} [G(x,x') - G_{\text{div}}(x,x')], 

where $\mathcal{D}_{\mu\nu}$ is a differential operator obtained from the classical stress tensor, and $G_{\text{div}}$ subtracts the local divergences. For time-dependent cavities, we use an adiabatic subtraction: $G_{\text{div}}$ is taken as the propagator in a locally static cavity with the same instantaneous geometry. This yields a finite, time-dependent stress tensor that includes contributions from created particles.

In the mode decomposition, the stress tensor can be expressed as a sum over modes. For the one-dimensional cavity, the energy density is

\langle T_{00}(x,t) \rangle = \frac{1}{2} \sum_n \left[ |\dot{q}_n(t)|^2 |u_n(x;t)|^2 + \omega_n^2(t) |q_n(t)|^2 |u_n(x;t)|^2 + \text{cross terms} \right] + \text{subtraction}. 

The mode amplitudes $q_n(t)$ are determined by the initial conditions (vacuum) and the dynamics (3.1). Their expectation values involve products of creation and annihilation operators; after renormalization, one obtains finite expressions.

5.2 Back-Reaction Force on Boundaries

The force on a boundary is given by the integral of the normal-normal component of the stress tensor over the boundary surface. For a one-dimensional cavity with a moving mirror at $x = L(t)$, the force on that mirror is

F(t) = \langle T_{xx}(L(t),t) \rangle. 

Using the mode expansion and the boundary conditions, one can derive an expression for $F(t)$ in terms of the mode amplitudes. For multi-scale driving, we find that the force contains oscillatory components at all driving frequencies and their combinations.

Proposition 5.1 (Vacuum friction spectrum): Consider a cavity driven at frequencies $\{\omega_i\}$ with amplitudes $\epsilon_i$. To leading order in $\epsilon_i$, the back-reaction force on a moving boundary is

F_{\text{back}}(t) = \sum_i F_i \cos(\omega_i t + \phi_i) + \sum_{i<j} F_{ij}^+ \cos[(\omega_i+\omega_j)t + \phi_{ij}^+] + \sum_{i<j} F_{ij}^- \cos[(\omega_i-\omega_j)t + \phi_{ij}^-] + \text{higher order}. 

The coefficients $F_i$, $F_{ij}^\pm$ are given by

F_i = \epsilon_i \omega_i^2 \times (\text{cavity geometry factor}) \times \mathcal{F}_i, 


F_{ij}^\pm = \epsilon_i \epsilon_j \omega_i \omega_j \times (\text{overlap factor}) \times \mathcal{F}_{ij}^\pm, 

where $\mathcal{F}_i$, $\mathcal{F}_{ij}^\pm$ are dimensionless functions of the mode structure and the driving phases. In particular, $F_{ij}^-$ depends on the relative phase $\phi_i - \phi_j$, providing a clear experimental signature. The phase-sensitive $F_{ij}^-$ terms (beat notes) could manifest as sidebands in cavity force-noise or displacement spectra, measurable in optomechanical readout or via circuit-QED homodyne detection of emitted radiation, distinguishing multi-scale from single- or commensurate driving.

Proof sketch. The force is obtained by inserting the mode expansion into $\langle T_{xx} \rangle$. To first order in $\epsilon$, the mode amplitudes $q_n$ contain terms oscillating at the driving frequencies. Their squares and products generate sum and difference frequencies. The expectation values of bilinears of creation and annihilation operators give the vacuum contribution (which is zero for normally ordered products) plus the contribution from created particles. The latter are of order $\epsilon^2$, so the $F_i$ terms come from interference between the zero-point motion and the first-order perturbation, while $F_{ij}^\pm$ come from second-order processes. A detailed derivation requires solving the mode equations perturbatively up to second order. ∎

5.3 Energy Conservation and Dissipation

The back-reaction force does work on the moving boundary. The power dissipated into the field is

P(t) = F_{\text{back}}(t) \dot{L}(t). 

Averaging over a long time, this must equal the energy carried away by created particles. This provides a consistency check on the calculations.

Observation 5.2 (Momentum conservation): In a closed system with perfectly reflecting boundaries, the total momentum of field plus boundaries is conserved. Integrating the stress tensor over a large spacetime region containing the system and using Stokes' theorem, one finds that any momentum gained by the boundaries is balanced by radiation momentum. Consequently, the center of mass of the system cannot accelerate. This is a direct consequence of $\partial_\mu T^{\mu\nu}=0$ and the absence of external forces.

