Appendix E: Numerical Methods for Multi-Scale DCE

E.1 Solving the Mode Equations

The coupled mode equations (3.1) form a system of second-order ODEs. For numerical solution, we rewrite them as first-order system:

\dot{q}_n = p_n, 


\dot{p}_n = -\omega_n^2(t) q_n - \sum_m [A_{nm}(t) p_m + B_{nm}(t) q_m]. 

We truncate to a finite number of modes $n=1,\ldots,N_{\text{max}}$, with $N_{\text{max}}$ chosen such that higher modes are not significantly excited (convergence checked by increasing $N_{\text{max}}$). The initial conditions are those of the vacuum state: $q_n(0)$ and $p_n(0)$ are Gaussian random variables with zero mean and covariance $\langle q_m q_n \rangle = \frac{\hbar}{2\omega_n}\delta_{mn}$, $\langle p_m p_n \rangle = \frac{\hbar\omega_n}{2}\delta_{mn}$ (for a scalar field). Alternatively, one can evolve the covariance matrix directly.

For incommensurate frequencies, we need to integrate over a long time to resolve beat frequencies. Adaptive integrators (e.g., Runge-Kutta-Fehlberg) are suitable. We use SciPy's solve_ivp with dense output to interpolate solutions at arbitrary times.

E.2 Computing Bogoliubov Coefficients

The Bogoliubov coefficients can be extracted from the mode functions. If we evolve a complete set of initial conditions corresponding to positive frequency modes at $t=0$, the resulting solutions at time $t$ give the mixing. For a finite number of modes, we construct the symplectic transformation matrix and obtain $\alpha$ and $\beta$.

Alternatively, we can compute $\beta$ via the formula $\beta_{nm} = \langle \psi_n^{\text{out}}, \psi_m^{\text{in}} \rangle$, where $\psi_n$ are mode functions. Numerically, we evolve a basis of initial conditions and project onto final modes.

E.3 Fourier Analysis of Output

To obtain the particle spectrum, we perform a Fourier transform of the evolved field operator or of the correlation functions. For incommensurate driving, the spectrum will show peaks at all combination frequencies $\mathbf{n}\cdot\boldsymbol{\omega}$. The heights of these peaks give $C_{\mathbf{n}}$. We use a windowed Fourier transform with long time integration to resolve dense frequencies.

E.4 Code Structure

The numerical code (to be made available on GitHub) will consist of:

· A module to construct $L(t)$, $\dot{L}(t)$, $\omega_n(t)$, $A_{mn}(t)$, $B_{mn}(t)$ for given driving parameters.
· An ODE solver for the mode equations.
· A post-processing module to compute spectra, squeezing parameters, and back-reaction forces.
· Visualization scripts.

The code will be written in Python with NumPy/SciPy, and optionally in Julia for performance.

